[[File:Okunitama Jinja Iwaki Ichinotorii.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|First torii}}]]
'''Ōkunitama Shrine''' (おおくにたまじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945}} in {{ill|lt=Taira Suganami|Q128846854|WD=Q128846854}}, {{ill|lt=Iwaki|Q274384|WD=Q274384}}, {{ill|lt=Fukushima Prefecture|Q71707|WD=Q71707}}. It is a {{ill|lt=small Shikinaisha|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=small Shikinaisha}} and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534}} was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=UNKNOWN|WD=Q90139226}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|lt=Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto|WD=Q276944}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN|WD=Q8009611}}
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN|WD=Q3275687}}

=== History ===
[[File:Kabutoduka Kohun.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|[[Kabutozuka Kofun (Iwaki)|Kabutozuka Kofun]]}}{{small|One theory views it as the tomb of {{ill|lt=Iwaki no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11585422|WD=Q11585422}}.}}]]

According to shrine tradition, in the {{ill|lt=Enryaku|Q1373176|WD=Q1373176}} era of {{ill|lt=Emperor Kanmu|Q314846|WD=Q314846}}, when Seii Taishōgun {{ill|lt=Sakanoue no Tamuramaro|Q941979|WD=Q941979}} passed through this area under imperial order to subdue the eastern barbarians, he found an old shrine badly devastated. After asking local people and learning it was Ōkunitama Shrine, he prayed for victory; after the enemy was pacified soon after, he built a large shrine in thanksgiving.

Ancient ruins nearby include Nara-period temple remains and {{ill|lt=Kabutozuka Kofun (Iwaki)|Q17990175|WD=Q17990175|lt=Kabutozuka Kofun}}. Because volume 10 "Kuni-no-Miyatsuko Honki" of '{{ill|lt=Sendai Kuji Hongi|Q2716751|WD=Q2716751}}' includes "{{ill|lt=Iwaki no Kuni no Miyatsuko|Q11585422|WD=Q11585422}}," this area is inferred to have been their base, with this shrine considered their clan shrine and Kabutozuka Kofun their tomb. Also, {{ill|lt=Iwaki Province|Q1192809|WD=Q1192809}} was established for several years from {{ill|lt=Yōrō|Q1373061|WD=Q1373061}} 2 ({{ill|lt=718|Q23534|WD=Q23534}}), and this area is also considered a possible provincial capital site.

Later, in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932}} it was ranked as small shrine. It was deeply revered by successive local lords, and in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963}}, donations of mikoshi, confirmation of documents, and construction of shrine buildings were successively made by the {{ill|lt=Naitō clan|Q2975325|WD=Q2975325}} and {{ill|lt=Andō clan|Q11451352|WD=Q11451352}}, lords of {{ill|lt=Iwakitaira Domain|Q843782|WD=Q843782}}.

=== Cultural properties ===
; Kunitama Documents (Fukushima Prefecture designated Important Cultural Property)
: Ancient documents from the {{ill|lt=Kamakura period|Q236205|WD=Q236205}} to the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|WD=Q264012|lt=Nanboku-chō period}}. Together with the Yatsuki and Iino document groups, they are important medieval historical materials. Among them, documents bearing sleeve seals of {{ill|lt=Kitabatake Akiie|Q1036864|WD=Q1036864}} and {{ill|lt=Ashikaga Takauji|Q297107|WD=Q297107}}, and the "old genealogy" identifying the founder of the {{ill|lt=Iwaki clan|Q11474314|WD=Q11474314}}, are especially important.

=== Precinct ===
The honden is designated an Iwaki City tangible cultural property.

<gallery>
File:Okunitama Jinja Iwaki Honden.jpg|Honden
File:Okunitama Jinja Iwaki Kaguraden.jpg|Kagura hall
</gallery>

=== Transportation ===
* From {{ill|lt=Iwaki Station|Q5353428|WD=Q5353428}} on the {{ill|lt=Jōban Line|Q1369263|WD=Q1369263}}, take {{ill|lt=Shin Jōban Kōtsū|Q11502130|WD=Q11502130}} bus bound for Nishihara via Natsui, get off at "Ōkunitama Shrine" bus stop
* 1 minute by car from the grade-separated junction of {{ill|lt=National Route 6|Q1038714|WD=Q1038714}} {{ill|lt=Jōban Bypass|Q11481556|WD=Q11481556}} and {{ill|lt=Fukushima Prefectural Route 229 Kabutozuka Kofun Line|Q11593467|WD=Q11593467}}

